				<article class=3D"post-3050 neve_custom_layouts type-neve_custom_layout=
s status-publish hentry">
<p class=3D"repeated-title">Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange</p>



<p></p>
</article><div class=3D"nv-content-wrap entry-content"><div class=3D"series=
box"><p>This article is a part of a&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://www.practicalne=
tworking.net/series/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">series</a>&nbsp;on=
 <a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/cryptog=
raphy/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Cryptography</a>. Use the naviga=
tion boxes to view the rest of the articles.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong><a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptograp=
hy/cryptography/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">Cryptography</a></stro=
ng></p>
<ul class=3D"serieslist-ul"><li class=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=3D"https://=
www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/hashing-algorithm/" title=
=3D"Hashing Algorithm">Hashing Algorithm</a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-l=
i"><a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/messa=
ge-integrity/" title=3D"Message Integrity">Message Integrity</a></li> <li c=
lass=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/serie=
s/cryptography/confidentiality/" title=3D"Confidentiality">Confidentiality<=
/a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetwor=
king.net/series/cryptography/symmetric-encryption/" title=3D"Symmetric Encr=
yption">Symmetric Encryption</a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=
=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/asymmetric-encr=
yption/" title=3D"Asymmetric Encryption">Asymmetric Encryption</a></li> <li=
 class=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/ser=
ies/cryptography/using-asymmetric-keys/" title=3D"Using Asymmetric Keys">Us=
ing Asymmetric Keys</a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=3D"https:/=
/www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/authentication/" title=3D"=
Authentication">Authentication</a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-li"><a href=
=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/anti-replay/" t=
itle=3D"Anti-Replay">Anti-Replay</a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-li"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/rsa-example/"=
 title=3D"RSA Example">RSA Example</a></li> <li class=3D"serieslist-li-curr=
ent"><strong>Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange</strong></li></ul><div class=3D"cl=
ear"></div></div>
<p>How can two people in a crowded room derive a secret that only the pair =
know, without revealing the secret to anyone else that might be listening?<=
/p>



<p>That is exactly the scenario&nbsp;the Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange exists=
 to solve.</p>



<p>The <strong>Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange is a means for two parties to jo=
intly establish a shared secret over an unsecure channel</strong>, without =
having any prior knowledge of each other.</p>



<p>They never actually exchange the secret, just some values that both comb=
ine which let them attain the same resulting value.</p>



<p>Conceptually, the best way to visualize the Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange =
is with the ubiquitous <a href=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/co=
mmons/4/46/Diffie-Hellman_Key_Exchange.svg" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopen=
er">paint color mixing</a> demonstration. It is worth quickly reviewing it =
if you are unfamiliar with it.</p>



<p>However, in this article we want to go a step further and actually show =
you the math in the Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">DH Math</h3>



<p>Before you get into the math of Diffie-Hellman, you will want to have a =
basic understanding of what a <strong>Prime</strong> number is, and what th=
e <strong>Modulus</strong> operation is (aka, remainder division). Both of =
these terms have been defined in <a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetworking=
.net/series/cryptography/rsa-example#terminology" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"=
noopener">another article</a>.</p>



<p>Below is an infographic outlining all the steps of the Diffie-Hellman ex=
change between Alice and Bob.</p>



<div class=3D"wp-block-image"><figure class=3D"aligncenter"><img fetchprior=
ity=3D"high" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1024" height=3D"751" src=3D"https:=
//www.practicalnetworking.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/dh-revised-1024x75=
1.png" alt=3D"Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange" class=3D"wp-image-256"></figure>=
</div>



<p>Notice how both Alice and Bob were able to attain the same Shared Secret=
 of 3. Anyone listening in on their DH Key exchange would only know the Pub=
lic Values, and the starting P and G values. There is no consistent way to =
combine those numbers (13, 6, 2, 9) to attain 3.</p>



<p>If you=E2=80=99d like to try it yourself, here are some combinations of =
Prime numbers and Generators you can use:  </p>


<div class=3D"table-responsive"><table style=3D"width:200px;  margin-left:a=
uto;margin-right:auto" class=3D"easy-table easy-table-default table-condens=
ed">
<tbody>
<tr><td><strong>Prime</strong></td>
<td><strong>Generator</strong></td>
</tr>

<tr><td>227</td>
<td>17</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>347</td>
<td>19</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>991</td>
<td>22</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table></div>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">DH Numbers</h3>



<p>In our example, we used a Prime number of 13. Since this Prime number is=
 also is used as the Modulus for each calculation, the entire key space for=
 the resulting Shared Secret can only ever be 0-12. The bigger this number,=
 the more difficult a time an attacker will have in brute forcing your shar=
ed secret.</p>



<p>Obviously, we were using very small numbers above to help keep the math =
relatively simple. True DH exchanges are doing math on numbers which are va=
stly larger:</p>


<div class=3D"table-responsive"><table style=3D"width:200px;  margin-left:a=
uto;margin-right:auto" class=3D"easy-table easy-table-default table-condens=
ed">
<tbody>
<tr><td>DH Group 1</td>
<td>768 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 2</td>
<td>1024 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 5</td>
<td>1536 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 14</td>
<td> 2048 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 15</td>
<td> 3072 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 16</td>
<td> 4096 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 17</td>
<td> 6144 bits</td>
</tr>

<tr><td>DH Group 18</td>
<td> 8192 bits</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table></div>



<p>The <strong>number of bits</strong> is a reference to the <strong>size o=
f the Prime number</strong>. This directly equates to the entire key space =
of the resulting Shared Secret. To give you an idea of just how large this =
key space is:</p>



<p>In order to fully write out a 768 bit number, you would need <a href=3D"=
http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=3D2%5E768" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"no=
referrer noopener nofollow">232 decimal digits</a>.<br>In order to fully wr=
ite out a 1024 bit number, you would need <a href=3D"http://www.wolframalph=
a.com/input/?i=3D2%5E1024" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nof=
ollow">309 decimal digits</a>.<br>In order to fully write out a 1536 bit nu=
mber, you would need <a href=3D"http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=3D2%5E=
1536" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">463 decimal di=
gits</a>.<br>In order to fully write out a 2048 bit number, you would need =
<a href=3D"https://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=3D2%5E2048" target=3D"_bla=
nk" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">617 decimal digits</a>.</p>



<p>The wild thing is <strong>every DH group below 2048 bit is considered no=
 longer secure by today=E2=80=99s standards</strong>. It is recommended to =
only use DH Group 14 and above.  Or, move on to Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellm=
an, but that will be a subject for another article.</p>



<p>The concept of a <em>group</em> in the <strong>DH Groups</strong> above =
is in reference to the starting values. Notice in the illustration above, A=
lice and Bob start with a Prime number and a Generator (13 and 6). These st=
arting values are pre-selected in various Diffie-Hellman RFCs. <a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2409" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer =
noopener nofollow">RFC 2409</a> define <a href=3D"https://www.rfc-editor.or=
g/rfc/rfc2409#section-6.1" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nof=
ollow">DH Groups 1 and 2</a>, and <a href=3D"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc=
/rfc3526" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">RFC 3526</=
a> define <a href=3D"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc3526#section-2" targ=
et=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener nofollow">DH groups 5, 14, 15, 16,=
 17, and 18</a>.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Using the Shared Secret</h3>



<p>Once the Shared Secret has been attained, it typically becomes used in t=
he calculation to establish a joint <a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetwork=
ing.net/series/cryptography/symmetric-encryption/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D=
"noopener">Symmetric Encryption key</a>&nbsp;and/or a joint <a href=3D"http=
s://www.practicalnetworking.net/series/cryptography/integrity/" target=3D"_=
blank" rel=3D"noopener">HMAC Key</a> =E2=80=93 also known as Session Keys.<=
/p>



<p>But it is important to point out that <a href=3D"https://www.practicalne=
tworking.net/practical-tls/rsa-diffie-hellman-dsa-the-pillars-of-asymmetric=
-cryptography/#dh-keys" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">the Shared Secre=
t itself should not directly be used as the Secret Key</a>. If it were, all=
 you can be assured of is that throughout the secure conversation you are s=
till speaking to the same party that was on the other side of the Diffie-He=
llman exchange.</p>



<p>However, you still have no confirmation or assurance as to who the other=
 party is. Just that no one else can all of a sudden pretend to be them in =
the middle of your secure conversation.</p>



<p>The generation of the actual Session Keys should include the DH Shared S=
ecret, along with some other value that would only be known to the intended=
 other party, like something from the <a href=3D"https://www.practicalnetwo=
rking.net/series/cryptography/authentication/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener">Authentication </a>scheme you chose.</p>



