they decide to do Diffie-Hellman to begin with.  </p>
<p>In <em>that</em> communication, the peers agree on a specific Diffie-Hel=
lman =E2=80=9Cgroup=E2=80=9D, which each have pre-determined Prime and Gene=
rator values.</p>
<p>For instance, in IPsec/ISAKMP, the peers agree on a Diffie-Hellman group=
 (2, 5, 14, etc..). Each of those are defined with a specific Prime / Gener=
ator in mind.  This article defines the Prime &amp; Generators for DH group=
s 1, 2, 3, and 4:</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2409#section-6" rel=3D"nofo=
llow ugc">https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2409#section-6</a></p>
<p>(note, not all are considered secure by today=E2=80=99s age)</p>

</div>
